Current state of the studio. 

I had my first full day at work. It was the best ever ever. I’ve been taking time with settling. With feeling things out. With aligning vibes and making sure things feeeeel good. 

So the shelves are not unpacked. My work desk is cluttered. The vintage pink velvet chairs probably need to move elsewhere. 

But I’m happy. So happy.

What are your 2023 planner plans?

I’ve become ridiculous.

Getting really settled into the Hobonichi Weeks. Attached to it. Still loving my Cousin and quite sad I have the A6 for next year. Sad enough, actually, that I decided to buy the HON and the Common Planner too. I have far too many planners for next year but I also have actual FOMO and too many fountain pens thanks to ramping up that hobby this year. And fountain pens require Tomoe River paper right? 

But I do not have enough life to fill these pages …

Bits of the studio in December.

I have been reaching flow more times in the last two weeks than I have the rest of the year. I mean. It’s more because I am down one ovarian cyst and one twisted ovary, and less because of this space. But this space…. it has magic in it. 

There is space for the heart to be made tangible here. There is glitter made of light against the wall. My own pops of colour against the stark white. Bits of my friends held in paper in this space. Thread holding together my thoughts and my releases. My meter long screen. And me.
One creative exploration I started this year is fountain pens and ink. Highly not recommended if you like having money. I’m at 20 pens and 52 inks now 😬 it happens like an avalanche.

2023 vision board and goals. This is the year of setting things on fire.

This is the fourth year of using a vision board. I make it in Procreate and Photoshop and I get the images from Unsplash and *myself*. 

If I had one tip for vision boarding it would be to add your own photos, drawing, lettering, and art.

If I had two tips for vision boarding, the second would be to make it passively visible. I put mine in the two places I visit every day - Notion (duh) and my paper planner.

I create it. Occasionally see it. Ignore it in the front part of my brain. The universe / magic does the rest. For the previous two years, my vision boards were replaced by actual images. In 2021, I used a stock photo to represent a full-time employee. The year ended with a real-life fantastic human, who pointed out that she looked just like that stock image. 

I don't see goals and intentions as a way of becoming someone entirely "better" than us, but rather as ways of becoming MORE ourself. Alignment. Living closer to your heart.

What's your word? What are your goals? Do you make vision boards?

Happy 2023 from my not-quite-aligned sign and pinkish disco ball. 

I haven't yet figured out how to hang him from the drop ceiling so I move him around throughout the day. I also haven't figured out what to put on either side of the apothecary / grandpa's wonky tool drawers / library catalogue setup. 

The new space has been really good for me. Tomorrow, 8 chairs arrive for the "workshop room". Am I hosting workshops in person? No(t yet?). Am I putting the chairs out in anticipation of bums? Yes. 

I'm making literal space, and the universe is just gonna have to fill it.

Here's to a 2023 that holds promise. Even if we don't yet know what that promise is gonna end up looking like.
State of the studio in the new year. Making my childhood dreams come true with a colour scheme that matches the Get Messy Brand, and with a friend (P) who sends me haiku mobiles.

I think I’ve found planner peace! I have been struggling since like September last year about the planner to use for this year. I’ve loved the Sterling Ink Common Planner but hated the daily pages for pedantic reasons. And then I found the Papertess Designs Yearly Notebook.

You guys, it has month/week/daily in ORDER and combined by month rather than combining by month/week/daily pages. I’m in love.

🕊️🕊️🕊️✌🏻✌🏻✌🏻

I filmed an unboxing (cause, damn it was packaged beautifully) and a comparison of the two because it helped me process my thoughts.

Feels good to fly this close to planner perfection.

Unbox and flip through the Papertess Designs Yearly Notebook. This is my 2023 planner, my baby, the one who brought me planner peace after way too much internet planner strife. I now officially have it all figured out. 😉

#papertessdesigns #papertessyearlynotebook #b6planner #plannercommunity #sterlinginkcommonplanner

How it started and how it’s going. Planner edition. 

Swipe and cringe at my 2007 planner. Back then, all I had were South African Cosmopolitans as collage fodder, kokis (markers), and emo song lyrics and weird quotes from friends. 

I have a love/hate relationship with paging through these but they do have bits of treasure - like the memory of Dr Christian Troy in Nip/Tuck. I asked for celeb crushes in my IG Story and am LOVING the answers. I’d love to know yours too.

Pages from my planner. 

Birds and florals from @ellymack_ 
Fairy Artmother badge from @janet.joehlin 

The goddess came from an idea from a book called Wishcraft. You create a muse for your goals, wants, heart. She looks after them and guides your path. I took a few photos of my nana, my favourite person, and ran them through an AI to get something that looks kinda sorta like her but also very much more like a goddess.

We were talking about goals in German class yesterday … about how they’re silly and you end up giving up after two weeks. 

I LOVE goals. If you have goals that just make you feel bad then you’re doing them wrong. They don’t need to be SMART goals or big goals or anything other than what you would like. Goals are just a reminder of what your heart wants. You can put something you’re already rocking on your goal list as a reminder that you’re already doing the thing you love. 

Goals are for YOU, the you that you currently are, not a “new and improved” version. They should be kind. 

Goals don’t *have* to be reached, either. A goal of journaling every day is still successful if you manage it 1/365. Doing something nice for yourself is a celebration even if you manage it once. 

Goals are a snapshot of what’s important to you at that moment in time. It’s your own little mission statement and you get to update it as often as you’d like.

Goals let you dig and figure out and articulate and remind yourself what’s important. You bring the depths of your heart to the surface.

Anyways, here are mine. The most cliche they’ve been in years, but after 2022 my heart is looking for some cliche.

I still haven’t been creating anything I’m able to show but I have been creating my own happiness in the form of my dog in my studio. #griffingrey

I started officially Making Art™️ in 2014. Since then, my keenness, my ability, my creative well levels, my amount of “free time”, have all waned. I “leave” art journaling, I let it simmer, I come back. 

It is the simple act of coming back that makes things worthwhile. The simple act of trying.

This time I’m coming back simply. A small gesture. Letting the muse know I’m here if she’d like to hang out …

There is a topic I've been exploring in my art journal for seven years now. It hasn't been an easy topic to explore, but I knew that it was very much needed and I continued. 

I've wandered off the journey, wandered back to it. It hasn't looked remotely similar at each stage, but this constant returning is what has grown my heart.

Over the years I've seen a very small handful of other creatives exploring the topic too. It's something that requires courage and vulnerability in equal measures. A layer of kindness, and another entire layer of brave when you share pieces of it. 

The topic is my (your) body.

The first time the idea came to create a class for this, I immediately shut it down. I knew that this is powerful but creating a class about the human body would probably mean I'd have to share my own body in some form, and eeeeek. 

The idea didn't leave, though. As much as I tried to push it out, it stayed on through the years. 

Finally, back in 2021, Brave Caylee put it on the calendar for 2023. I'd have time to prepare, I'd have time to make sure my body was perfect. 

The universe laughed at my plans, and 2022 was the roughest year for my body yet. I went through a life-altering surgery, which has forever changed my body. Through this, I gave up on the Perfect Body and in doing so, I was able to find so much more. My body became a thing of awe, not because of what it looked like, but because of its own healing. The journey of exploring my own body as art had so much more meaning to it. 

And so I'm here, showing up in 2023, being reminded of the value in sharing in the messy middle. The beauty in the imperfect. My inner critic, the loud fear within me is yelling, but I'm ignoring them and letting you know that Body of Art is now open for enrollment through @getmessyartjournal .

These are the journals I spent every single day in January in. 

Bottom to top:
Elliot’s 5 Year journal (Hobonichi A5) with the memories I’m keeping for him 

Daily planner (@papertessdesigns) for work and processing. 

Written journal (Stalogy B6) that I word vomit into, whose insides are never allowed to see the light of day. 

Health planner (Hobo Weeks) for planning, uh, health. 

Quantified Life (Hobo A6) for daily tracking and logging and it’s the biggest surprise how much I have adored this. 

Passport TN for writing absolute nonsense in, but it has a pigeon pin on it so things are grand.

The non-illustrated stack of daily journals I’m checking into. 

I finally have successfully created a journaling and (gentle) tracking habit that integrates with my life. It’s aligning so beautifully. 

At the beginning of the day I word vomit my brain onto paper (or if you prefer elegance, I allow the breathings of my heart to flutter onto the page). this is the fabric covered Stalogy.

As soon as I get to work I open the Papertess daily planner and map the day.

After T has put our son to bed, I sit on the couch with a fluffy blanket and log my day in the weeks and the A6 Hobonichi.

The 5 Year journal is left out next to the couch for writing bits of my son into. 

The TN is carried around for whipping out a notebook rather than my phone.

Beautifully seamless and a day filled with paper and words rather than scrolling 🖤 working for me in this season.

Nahvalur - Rabbit Pen of the Year unboxing.

This baby is limited edition and is one of 223 worldwide. Pearl white resin with bits of pink and blue. Warm rose gold trim. 14k gold nib in medium. And a fun piston filler mechanism that makes me very nervous. 

She’s a thick boi and I love her.

Exploring my body through my art journal. As always, my journal helps me see. It helps me feel.

The Body of Art class at @getmessyartjournal has been such an intense journey of vulnerability. Seeing the art that has come from it and the individual brave journeys has given courage to continue.
Liquid charcoal. It’s made of magic.
My acrylic signage arrived 🥳 it’s not up yet but that doesn’t mean I’m less excited.

Todays the last day of Body of Art over at Get Messy and there is a host of feelings alongside it. Exploring your body in your journal is not really a journey that ever ends per se but this chapter I’m sad to say goodbye to. Also glad in some ways.

It’s been a big stretch in vulnerability and so I haven’t shared much here. Plus, not so keen to have my naked body on IG, that’s for paying members only (kidding!).

I am a prolific scanner. I don’t like clutter but I’m exceptionally organised digitally and so I turn paper into digital hoarding. 

So I have a bunch of my journals scanned in. When I was printing out @erin_ware_journaling’s gorgeous bits from Patreon and had a small bit of space for the sticker paper I put this guy in. Turns out I needed him because I needed a restart. Stuck some of Erin’s flowers on top of it and bam. Happiness in my planner. 🌸

Meet Eleanor. Or Pearl / Willow / Peggy / Wilhelma. Uh. I’m not quite sure yet. Some seriously great names suggested - some I’ve already used for phones and computers and cars.

Regardless of her name, she’s a secretary (Sekretär) from the 1960s. She’s been SO well looked after. She smells like old woman perfume (my fave). I traveled to a tiny village, up a steep hill and then another two flights of stairs to get her. And she fits SO well in the studio. 

My plan is to use her for my written journals. I don’t think she can handle mixed media and I don’t want to try and see. But she’ll be the home for my self exploration. Connection. Resets. And realignment.

Was foraging deep into the forest in a tiny German village and buying a cheap secretary from the 60s just for my written journaling kinda ridiculous? Yes, but my husband doesn’t allow furniture with character at home.

The entirety of this year I have been oscillating between journals. Besides my daily journals I cannot seem to find a rhythm for my “art” journal. “” because these are all self-imposed names, but assigning journals helps me. 

Plain sketchbook? Altered vintage book? Rebinding a vintage book? Travelers notebooks? Tiny pamphlet stitch? None of them is sticking. Maybe it’s time for a new Get Messy journal?

What are you currently using?

I shared in my stories about my current creative feelings. I’m all dried up. I’m feeling so much resistance to making art. So much resistance to creating.

It doesn’t mean I don’t desperately want to, though. I waaaaant to but my ass is not going where my heart wants it to be. 

And so I forced myself. I don’t usually agree with this method but I needed it. 

And in the same way you wrap your dogs medication in some cheese, I stood at my desk knowing I only had 15 minutes and I managed to cut up this half-used Hobonichi to prep it for a travel journal. Tomorrow I’ll force another 15 minutes. I’ll wrap up my creating in some cheese and trick myself to do what I really, really wanna do.

Day two of wrapping my creating with cheese. I’ve cut apart my floral Hobonichi and am replacing it with my own paper. I managed to do the cover and inside, and collect paper for binding. 

Bookbinding is a good way for me to return to my art, return to self. It’s a harmony of my right and left brain, and my left brain is LOUD during these downtimes. 

I’ve had a lot of really good, practical ways to come back to art in a low pressure way. For when you want to be kind to yourself but you also really want to actually make art. 

Move paper around. Scream. Go for a walk. Try something totally different. Invite a friend. Those are some of my favourites and I know I’m forgetting a few.

I bound my journal! I cut up this gorgeous Hobonichi Weeks (loved the cover, didn’t love the insides). Cut up three Travelers Notebook inserts (extra thin, kraft, and watercolour). Put them back together. Added a magazine page of pure South African delight. 

I used gel matte medium to add one of my favourite pieces of ephemera ever found (a handwritten letter to “my dear banana” that I found in South Africa). And I didn’t hate it. 

Taking this on our trip. Low pressure. Adding ephemera. Doodles. Writing.

This is our last trip to South Africa as South Africans and it’s bringing up so many feelings. To become German citizens we have to give up our original citizenship and it’s hard on the heart no matter what the logistics are.

And so it was important to have a journal for this trip. I don’t usually. But I’ve found it really wonderful to spend the time sitting and reflecting and doodling and drawing a lot of little hermit crabs from my day.

This Hobonichi x TN x custom binding has turned out beautifully.

Two nights without E (only our second time away from him in his six years). 

T goes running every morning and so I journal. Writing. Doodling. Watercolours.

I’ve really been enjoying this Hobonichi/TN hybrid that I bound together -  super thin pages (dream, thanks to @janethecrazy for making me wanna use mine), Kraft (always a top fave) and watercolour paper (usually not a fan but the TN one is not the worst). The size has been a struggle and I’ve had to cut down a lot of paper I’d prefer to have larger but the floral cover is still part of my heart.
This Traveler’s Notebook is traveliiiiiiing

Adding D&D doodles to travel journals is a great way to chunk them up. 

And yes that is a moth melted in wax. We played by candlelight because of loadshedding (no electricity), he flew into a candle and looked beautiful so he went into the journal. 

Everything goes into the journal … even moth carcasses.
I really want to be a wicker basket journal person a la @brandi_kincaid but until I get there I’ll be using these to cart supplies between the studio and home 😍

I’m in a period of high anxiety and here’s how I’m caring for myself through it:

- carrying a tiny passport TN in my handbag with two inserts - a gorgeous insert by Yamamoto and TC’s super lightweight paper (obsessed)
- writing down every errand thought, anxiety driven impulse, getting it out of my head and onto paper
- doing so messily, without structure, without perfection
- making sure to use a fountain pen for smooooothness and aforementioned paper for loads of calming crinkle 
- keeping bits from @erin_ware_journaling and this amazing paper with my name on from @mylifemits 
- keeping my studio and happy place right in the front
- keeping my hearts (T, E, G) in photo form inside there too
It’s gonna be May 😍

This year my planner has been saving me. 

Last year was a bit of a disaster and this year is following its footsteps but I won’t give up the effort of finding good in the messy middle. It’s one thing to have “embrace the messy middle” written on the wall of the studio but it’s another to live it. To give myself bits of creativity and heart and goodness. 

I had a great convo with someone recently about art as documenting. It reminded me of how much that is good for me. Gratitude really is powerful. T has sent me a gratitude list every Sunday evening for FIVE years. He is a man of habit and routine and discipline and it’s insane to see. I am a person of bits. Small, repeated (a little irregular) effort. 

Writing down small bits of what happened allow me to find things to be grateful for right amongst the shit. Looking back at what I feel like has been a really hard year, I’m able to still see beauty. Thinking about all the things I had to let go of because of a sick child, I’m able to see all the dreams I had that DID get done. Despite it. Through it. Because of it. 

And seeing art from online friends, and adorable pigeons inside it is the icing on top.

(And PS my week has already changed plans because of a sick boy 🙄)
The most incredible package of gifts from Aunt T 🌸 including this journal. Perks of creative friends is their art as gifts. 😍

I’ve been keeping a health tracker and filling it in religiously every day. I started with a Hobonichi A6 Avec (Daily), then a Hobonichi Weeks, then a PTD Weekly, then the Hobo Weeks again. The daily didn’t have a decent weekly view. The PTD didn’t have enough space and the Hobo Weeks? I CANNOT get myself to love it. Cannot. Will I accept this fact after trying it out five separate times? Probably not. 

But I was watching my fellow Grey @itskaitlingrey’s video on her TN Weekly and something clicked. I do my health focuses in 12 week stretches, started a new one on Monday, and so it was perfect timing.

Paired it with my self coaching / coaching with Kelli journal (TN lightweight paper) and it’s a great partnership for this cover.

The cover itself has a star that I have wanted since forever from @erin_ware_journaling / @mylifemits, plus a South African beaded flag (beads are v traditional, it’s kitsch I love it). Covering notebooks in this simple way is my fave since highschool and I love Erin for bringing me back to it. 

Last pic is pure happiness and part of looking after my mental and physical health. 

Love this setup deeply so far except for one thing : I still hate using Travelers Notebooks in the leather cover. It makes for such a bumpy experience with any other notebook grouped together. Any tips for learning to love it?

The studio is quiet (too quiet!) again but remnants of the meet-up are still around. Half a happy birthday sign (@getmessyartjournal turned 9!), bits of ephemera, paint on the tables, a messy table that I refuse to clean up.

Remnants from the meetup (the last pic is my favourite!)

The polaroid wall has more faces on it. 

My ephemera stash was well and truly raided. 

Small bits left on the two-dining-tables-big art table. 

Happy. 

-

I've been waiting until I could put into words what this May meetup adventure meant to me. Jokes on me because I'm still not there, so I'll share messily. 

In May 2014, 9 years ago, Get Messy begun between two people. I could never have imagined that it would become what it is. 

I could never, in my wildest dreams, even begin to dream this whole thing up. I couldn't even imagine the ingredients that brought all of it together.

And then meeting in person.

Having V, G, E, C, P, A, L, H, M, and T breathing the same air as me? Having them share an art table, share supplies, physically write in my journal, let me TOUCH theirs (and SMELL theirs!). 

To see @myheartdreaming's handstitched Get Messy logo on her journal and her shirt. Laugh at @fern.and.oak.art's jokes in real time. Witness an actual halo of neon around @monaschreibt. Fall in love with @messianse's actual handmade shirt (and bravery). See @dansmoncrane sketch our collective supplies. Spot @gillywelch21's unicorn hair in a crowd. @lottefirlefanz's pure inspiration from her constant showing up through art. Feel the warmth from Phoebe's hug and presence.
Meet @marakreativstudio's adorable family and watch her lettering Get Messy into her journal. The creative partners, the good men.

To speak Afrikaans and Flemish and German and ENGLISH. To speak art journaling. 

To witness the shining lights from each artist, tangibly, in PERSON. It's an honour. I'm in awe of these women.

So I guess I didn't put anything into words. Just more "pinch me, I'm dreaming". 

I'm already looking at flights to the US for Get Messy's 10 years.

And next year is going to be even better ...

I got to chat and laugh (mainly laugh) with two of my favourite creatives @ruskea_art and @iris.impressions.art about turning your body into art. They recorded it. 

It's on the Not a Real Artist podcast - you know how to find it. 

"Society tells us all the ways in which our body is too much or not enough. We can reclaim our connection and relationship to our bodies through art. Give it permission to be art itself, to see it as an artist, to live in it as an artist. 

We can look at the details of our body, both outside and inside, as a way of starting a dialogue and connection with our body and appreciating it. Combining art and the body can help bring awareness to the parts of ourselves that we’ve buried or covered over."

Thank you so much for having me.
Bits from my Messy May journal. These papers represent a seismic shift within my artist self.
More pages from my Messy May journal. I adored pouring into it. The little drawings. The best washi tape. The pieces of other artists in there.
This is the first ever travel journal that didn’t follow chronologically. Not sure if I’d do it again but yes it was freedom.
A new season of creating is coming … there are signs …
It all needs to come out and I am so tired of self-censoring and holding myself back from myself.
Final pages from my journal in May.

One of the best things I’ve ever done in my journals was start with a “stats” page - date/age, where I’m at. Sometimes a photo. It’s a quick snapshot for future Caylee and a mindful moment for current Caylee.

Granting myself permission to create what I want. What I need. Create ugly stuff. Beautiful stuff. To show up with baggage, let it all out. Enjoy it. 

Also giving myself permission to *not* make if I don’t want to. And to be unapologetically excited about it all.

Made a cover for my Quantified Self journal. I’m using a Hobonichi Avec in A6. 

From Wikipedia:
Quantified self refers both to the cultural phenomenon of self-tracking with technology and to a community of users and makers of self-tracking tools who share an interest in "self-knowledge through numbers". Quantified self practices overlap with the practice of lifelogging and other trends that incorporate technology and data acquisition into daily life, often with the goal of improving physical, mental, and emotional performance. 

🥳

Mixing the art of other artists + my own. Jane’s printable journals and art send from Claudette via my mother 😍 

And my ever present reminder that I constantly need reminding of. More. Than. Zero.
Still in love with these words from @lizelayne. I’ve made so many journal pages with these nestled between them.
I’m hosting today’s Junk Journal July prompt - Details. I adore JJJ and I adore @megjournals for running it every year. My video’s up on YouTube - lemme know if you take on the challenge 😉

There are some new faces around here so I thought I’d reintroduce myself …

JUST KIDDING. 

Here’s to posting photos of ourselves amongst the paper just cause we feel like it. No reintroductions needed (unless you’d like to, that’s cool too).

I’m thrilled to be part of @thepigeonletters’ Summer Creative Retreat. I’ll be teaching The Recovering Perfectionist’s Guide to Making Art. One of my faaaaaave techniques. 

You can sign up (for free) at https://getmessyart.com/summer
Next month’s class at Get Messy is gonna be amaaaaaaaazing. I’m beyond excited tor Ama-ZINE.

Here are my un-shareable journals. 

I have pages and journals and even shelves of art that hasn’t been seen by anyone except me. After a passionate monologue from @claudette_hasenjager, I decided to put some of the journals together in a pile. 

It includes art I’m proud of, art that moved me, art that meant a lot. It also includes art that I hate, art I’m neutral about, art that is too x or too y. 

But sharing art has never been about curating the perfect feed for me. It’s never been about showing off or showing how “good” I am (I don’t think that and good/bad art is beside the point). Sharing art is about permission. 

Permission to make 365 pieces of art but only like 10. Permission to not enjoy all of it. Permission to make art, even with 10 minutes of free time. Permission to not make art at all. Permission to make weird art after having a baby. Permission to yearn for something from your art and not reach it, and show up anyway. Permission to show up. Permission to keep going. Permission to restart. 

When you make your art and when you share it in any form at all, you give permission. Here’s my pile of permission for you.
A new journal. A new front page with a photo + quick stats. June was really hard and July was really, really good. 💪🏻

I don’t have enough shelves for my journals so have had to create a new spot on my secretary. Brought the journals I’ve finished for Elliot to the studio because we need to make space for actual books on out home shelves.

Still in love with this piece 😍

Today marks the start of zine season over at Get Messy and I am celebrating finally being able to release this class into the membership. 8 incredible teachers. 8 very different ways of making zines. 1 big heart-driven class. 

This is the zine I’m teaching, it’s also the free lesson which you can grab at @getmessyartjournal. August is already looking great.

THE most beautiful vintage book I’ve found in a while. Found by @dansmoncrane, actually, while we were in Leipzig. 

My rule for these is to spend as much as I’d spend on a journal, which is around €30-40 or it can go higher if it’s special. 

The papers are shiny so I’ll be reminding it. 

What should I fill it with?

Find someone who looks like you the way I look at my journals. 

(this one is a @willa.wanders original and I still love it. miss this jersey. miss that wall. considering breaking down my new studio wallpaper to reveal the old red brick underneath)
Words from the catalog of unabashed gratitude by Ross Gay. My favourite kind of zine.

My inner child says hiiiii. Drew her with my left hand alongside a group of incredible women. 

Child Caylee loved pink and water and hated shirts. Not much has changed. 

It was fun getting to hang out with her today and the other kids 🩷

Document 👏 your 👏 creating.

Make evidence 👏 of 👏 making.

Remind yourself of your ability 👏 to 👏 show 👏 up 👏 .

In 2017, when my son was born, I felt like I lost my entire artist self. I felt as though I didn't make anything. It took a while, but eventually I responded to that by documenting each time I actually did show up for myself. A quick snap. Blurry. Ugly art. Art made at a table or while breastfeeding. All of it. Anything counted. 

By the end of that year I had *more than zero* photos of art making. Tangible proof. I was still making art. I was still an artist. Sometimes I lie to myself so offering my inner critic indisputable proof of Actual Showing Up was very soothing. Very helpful to continue to show up. 

I put those photos in an album on my computer (Slide 2).

In 2019, I moved into my first studio far from home, I brought my journals with. To ease up on the packing, I recycled almost all of them. But before doing so, I counted them. 284.

In 2020, I decided to draw them all.

In 2021, I decided to photograph them as a collection (ie: with a consistent background). This was insane. Saved them in Lightroom and gave each an album that had the photo and the drawing (Slide 3). 

In 2022, I decided to put them into a digital collection (Slide 4). I use Notion for it. I've been able to accurately name each journal. 

Is this insane? Absolutely yes. You can see I've stopped illustrating them for now. I go through illustrating seasons, and wordsy seasons, and I think this one is an artsy season. I include the number (v important to me because of Proof Of Making), photo (changed due to new studio, I miss that old wall), year (v important to me to get a numbered overview of what a year looks like in art - no judgies), what type of journal, and any tags (for journals I use often). 

I've called it Paper Trail.
Thank you, Rach.
Zines are good at holding it all.

Today was your funeral. It shouldn’t have been your funeral. There were so many good things ahead. I know your brain didn’t believe that but your brain was lying to you. We were trying to tell you. We tried to show you the good things. You were the good thing. 

You are the one who taught us to find beauty. We’ve become so good at it, you’d be so proud. You regularly found flowers in literal trash and made bouquets. Why couldn’t you make another bouquet. There was art left in you. Beauty left in you. Love love love surrounding you. 

You helped us find beauty in a country we hadn’t settled in. You were the settling in. You were my home why did you leave. We had more to show you. There was more. Where does the more go now. I’m sorry. I love you. What the fuck. I understand. I trust you. I’m so mad at you. I love you.

If you’re going through grief too (I hope you’re not) then may I suggest zines? You won’t feel any better but a tiny piece of your grief will live outside of you. And you can burn it or tear it up or drown it or throw up on it. 

Flowers in the trash printed. Typewritten words on vellum. Folded together and the flowers from sympathy bouquets tucked between the two. Rach, you would have loved this shit. I’m so pissed you’re gone. Paper was your love language. Flowers were too. And words. I miss your words. I liked making art TOGETHER. This is nonsense. Thank you for leaving me with so much. It wasn’t enough.

Today my grief looks like anger. 

I’m doing the @struthless69 #alphabetsuperset challenge (with my gracious and forgiving challenge partner @megjournals). One zine per week. 

I’m still making zines about the grief of losing a best friend. I would prefer another topic but I guess I’m grateful to be able to still move paper around. It helps it live outside of me. 

I’m using my typewriter to type (or today, punch) the letters and words onto a sheet of paper without thinking. Today it loosened the anxiety. 

Transparency film for today which is pretty tough to fold into a zine.

But. 

So many buts left behind. Buts that will remain buts. Remain unfinished. Remain unanswered and open and without closure. 

#alphabetsuperset challenge where I’m doing a zine a week with @megjournals and I’m hoping at some stage a letter will not be filled with grief and that I can make art that isn’t about my dead best friend but for now it’s helping. #getmessyzines

10.10.2023 

Something great is coming …
In 21 days the Big News will be revealed… I have not been this excited about anything since basically starting Get Messy. I hope you’ll get excited with me 😀
Yeah zines are cool and everything but have you ever held a friend’s zine in your hand? 😍 this piece of beauty is from @gillywelch21 and the TEXTURE and the NEON is maaaaagic.

(TW) This week’s zine is ugly. It’s an ugly topic (suicide). It’s not pretty art. The words are not pretty or fine tuned or articulate or even particularly kind. I didn’t even feel better after typing them up. I’m choosing not to share the whole zine, though I’d like you to know that you can make landscape zines too. 

Today grief is active and tangible and lumpy. Today is one month and four days since one of my best friends died by suicide. Today is part of suicide prevention month. 

I have been quite annoyed at the well-meaning typography on pastel backgrounds on social media - “check in on your friends”. Rachael was very well checked in on. In a hospital. Loved and cared for. I don’t know what the narrative *should* be or what the pretty pink backgrounds *should* say. I just know it needs to be more. More than this. Suicide doesn’t happen because people are not checked in on.

You are loved, you are loving, you are loveable. 

(Zine made as part of the #alphabetsuperset challenge, which is inadvertently helping process my grief through art. @megjournals and I are doing a zine a week and you’re welcome to join - no grief required)

My entire life revolves around getting you to make more art. 

Fitting art into your gloriously full life as it is right now. 

Get Messy’s next chapter is going to make your creative practice even better. 

But I couldn’t do it on my own. For this I called upon my very own fairy Artmother, Inked. The incredibly kind, passionate, and mutually excited humans who wave their wands to turn the dream tangible. 

In a practical way that looks like Get Messy art supplies and other creative catalysts to make YOU your favorite artist.

I seriously can’t wait to share these with you, but for now… it’s all starting with a journal.

Because of course.

The journal has mixed paper for true mixed media, and a host of other things specifically designed with the messy artist in mind. 

I can’t wait to share more. 

As all journalers know, the journal is only the beginning. 

We have such great plans for you and so many good things to come.

I’ve been stitching.
Revisiting this journal that was created for a journey with a group of incredible women. Adding thread to it which should come as no surprise to you at all.

This journal had remained unfinished for a while. Finished but not finished. You know those kinds of journals? I couldn’t put it away but I didn’t feel like it was the right time to keep working on it. 

Turns out it needed some stitches.
Holding space for the broad range of feelings right now. Excitement and hope and grief and fear and exhaustion and alignment and delight. I’m feeling all of them and they’re going into the journal.
The things that stitch me together.

Things I like:

Laminated flowers
Sewn neon thread
Typewritten words
Hyperbolic thoughts
Layers of journal

Grateful for:

Neon as a neutral. 

I have a lot on my plate but it’s all delicious (new fave saying). Big beautiful meeting tomorrow with big beautiful topics. 

Scanners that can kinda scan in neons. Kinda. But definitely threads. The Epson Perfection V600 if you’re wondering. 

Facials, where they do your eyebrows too. Face massages. 

Pens that write just right in the moment. 

End of month, esp end of year journaling. 

People like @claudette_hasenjager - who burn their journal and film it for an idea you had. 

A dog’s excitement when you get home. Or wake up. Or look at him. 

Dogs. Eternally dogs. 

People to talk to about your dead friend. 

Platinum Carbon Black Ink. 

A full planner or a full journal or so much evidence of your own showing up. 

Crocheted toilet seat covers. 

Spotify Wrapped and seeing your sons shitty taste in music amongst your own shitty taste in music. Your top song being one you played on repeat in the car, driving along a South African beach, shout singing along with your kid and sister. 

Knowing the perfect Christmas gift in time to get it before Christmas.

You guys.
This journal. 

Now I know I don't believe in perfection, but if perfection existed it would be this journal. 

Perfect size.
Perfect paper.
Perfect details. 
Perfectly wrapped.

And filled with very imperfect art. 

Bits of life on film by Natalie, we took the journal on an artist's date to Frankfurt. I cannot wait to see it in other places too (mainly: your studio, your kitchen table, your local coffee shop, near your face, in YOUR general vicinity). 

It's being released really, really soon. Very early 2024. THANK YOU for being excited with me. The excitement has been like a shower of glitter and now I'm hoping I've ordered enough of them. I don't want anyone to miss out on this glorious mix of perfection and imperfection. 

I'd love to hear if you're hoping to have your own journal like this + where you're planning to put it 😃

You may have heard me say "it all comes from the journal" before. Here's the beginning of what I shared a few posts back...

I make bold moves in the safe space of my journal so that I can make bold moves in the sometimes scary space outside of it.

I’m surprised by the quantity. I thought I’d put depth ahead of breadth. This year was an incredibly tough one and I’m proud of myself for letting it go into the journal. My creative year was a year of depth and processing and feeling everything through paper. Paper as parachute. 

A trip back to the hospital (that little yes TN saved me), exploring my body as art in a time where I was the most disconnected to it (altered book with stretchmarks), carrying the depression of a couple of my favourite people (mostly the canvas journal), realising everything I had left behind as an immigrant (floral, rebound Hobonichi), grieving one of my best friends leaving the country and then grieving her leaving this earth (zines). 

And then there are the details of delight. The biggest one, Get Messy’s partnership with Inked (the “yes” journal with the canvas ribbon), another year with Elliot (large canvas journal), Return to Self, MESSY MAY (being with other art journalers, and conversations on what it means to be an artist with @dansmoncrane), trying again and again and again and being knocked down and getting back up. 

The good, the bad, the buckling grief, the knees collapsing fear, the celebrations and the joy that’s uncontained in the journal, and pouring out. The life. The journals.

3 JANUARY 3 JANUARY 3 JANUARY

The best journal I’ve ever used will be available to grab as a pre-order on 3 January. I know I’m biased about it being the best, but I’m pretty certain it will be in your top faves. I filled up my sample in just over a week. 

I’m so proud of this journal. I’m so thrilled with how @inkedbrands took the dreams, my ideas based on all the journals that were * almost amazing *, how they made those all tangible, and the end result which is completely amazing. 

I think I’m gonna explode once I see the canvas ribbon in your home. Can’t wait to see how you customise the cover. Can’t wait to see what you do with the mixed paper and the pockets. Can’t wait to see the peek of yellow from the stitching. 

3 January 🥳

Eeeeeeeeeeeeee

Get Messy is turning 10 years old this year. 

A decade is a lot of time for dreaming. A lot of time to turn dreams into real life. We Messians have put on gallery shows, been in newspapers, and started magazines, written books, taught in person classes, become BFFs, started creative businesses, created podcasts, opened art stores, and made so so much art. As a community, we’ve collaborated with exciting humans and projects - too many to name. We wrote a book together! We created physical space in the world! We met up beyond our screens. 

There have been so many Big, Hairy, Audacious Dreams that became almost casual occurrences.

And it all stemmed from a journal.

We are embracing imperfection through sheets of paper bound together, with courage pulled from other wonderful humans doing the same.

Over the past decade, we have turned the messy middle into a revolution.

I say this a lot but we’re so much more than the sum of our parts. Get Messy would never have become what it is today if you never took the brave step to share your art and your heart in the way that feels true to you.

So when it was time to be brave and take steps towards one of Get Messy’s biggest, most audacious dreams... I knew I had to pull on support.

This community has grown so much that our next level needed exactly the right humans.

And I knew exactly who to call upon for help.

Getting to know the team at Inked and what is possible through them has been even better than I expected (and I expected a lot). They are heart-led, full of excitement, and really good at what they do. It’s my personal goal to convert each of them to art journaling so hopefully you’ll get to meet them too. In a package they sent me when we just started talking they signed a card “here’s to so many good things to come” and it’s become somewhat of a mantra. It’s something I can feel in my bones to be true for us - for Get Messy, for me, for you.
There are so many good things to come. So many dreams to be realized. So much art to be made. And I’m so excited that we get to make it tangible and practical for you.

I’m excited to share the details with you. But for now, all you need to do is to keep showing up.
